<HEADLINE>
<P>
PAKISTAN SAYS IT WILL REASSURE U.S. ON NUCLEAR PROGRAM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, Pakistan 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The government said Sunday that it will seek to reassure the United States that 
its controversial nuclear program is peaceful. 
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Ministry spokesman, quoted by the official APP news agency, said, 
"Pakistan never tried to manufacture a nuclear bomb, nor would it ever do so in 
the future." 
</P>
<P>
The statement followed American newspaper reports that U.S. aid to Pakistan 
might be cut off because Washington may no longer be able to certify that 
Pakistan does not possess a nuclear bomb. 
</P>
<P>
Without such certification, required annually by law, Pakistan would not be 
eligible to receive U.S. economic and military aid beyond the financial year 
ending on Sept. 30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
