</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The outlawed Irish Republican Army pledged to take greater care to avoid 
causing civilian casualties after its political supporters criticized the 
guerrilla group for a series of botched bomb attacks in Northern Ireland. The 
pledge came in a message from the IRA's "army council" to the annual conference 
in Dublin, Ireland, of the group's legal political arm, Sinn Fein. However, the 
IRA said it will continue attacks against British military and security forces. 
Twenty-three civilians have been killed since November, 1987, by the IRA in 
guerrilla operations that went wrong. 
