<TEXT>
<P>
Five fatal shootings in a 24-hour period made January the deadliest month ever 
in the nation's capital as Washington recorded 49 homicides. At the present 
pace, District of Columbia homicides would exceed 600 for the year. The 
District last year recorded 372 homicides, surpassing Detroit for the highest 
murder rate in the country. Police Chief Maurice T. Turner Jr. and Assistant 
Chief Isaac Fulwood Jr. are expected to unveil a proposal for dealing with the 
violence at a news conference today. Fulwood last week said the city's raging 
drug trade continues to be responsible for most of the gunplay. 
</P>
