<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Defending Sudanese troops ran out of ammunition and abandoned the southern 
garrison town of Nasir, besieged by rebels for more than nine months, the 
army's general command said. A statement said that more than 1,700 army and 
rebel troops were killed or wounded in the siege of the Upper Nile town. The 
official Sudan News Agency said that Col. Mahjoub Mohammed Yousif, commander of 
the garrison, was among those killed. The statement said government troops were 
forced to withdraw after bad weather interrupted air drops of much-needed 
ammunition and supplies. The fall of Nasir is seen as a major blow to the 
Khartoum government in the five-year-old civil war in the south. 
</P>
